        <!-- Clinical Examples Section -->
        <div class="clinical-examples-section">
          <h3>Clinical Examples</h3>
          <div class="examples-grid">
            <div class="example-card">
              <div class="example-header">
                <h4>Example 1: Focal Motor Seizure with Preserved Consciousness</h4>
              </div>
              <div class="example-content">
                <p><strong>Clinical presentation:</strong> A 35-year-old patient experiences rhythmic jerking of the right hand that gradually spreads to the right arm. The patient remains fully conscious and can recall the event afterward.</p>
                <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Focal motor onset seizure with preserved consciousness</p>
                <p><strong>EEG finding:</strong> Left central rhythmic discharges</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="example-card">
              <div class="example-header">
                <h4>Example 2: Absence Seizure</h4>
              </div>
              <div class="example-content">
                <p><strong>Clinical presentation:</strong> A 10-year-old child briefly stares, stops activity, and is unresponsive for about 10 seconds before resuming activity with no recollection of the event.</p>
                <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Generalized onset - typical absence</p>
                <p><strong>EEG finding:</strong> 3 Hz generalized spike-and-wave discharges</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="example-card">
              <div class="example-header">
                <h4>Example 3: Focal to Bilateral Tonic-Clonic</h4>
              </div>
              <div class="example-content">
                <p><strong>Clinical presentation:</strong> A 27-year-old experiences a visual aura followed by head turning to the right, then progressing to bilateral limb stiffening and jerking with loss of consciousness.</p>
                <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Focal to bilateral tonic-clonic seizure</p>
                <p><strong>EEG finding:</strong> Left occipital onset spreading to both hemispheres</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Diagnostic Decision Tree -->
        <div class="decision-tree-section">
          <h3>Seizure Classification Decision Tree</h3>
          <div class="decision-tree-container">
            <div class="decision-node start">
              <div class="node-content">
                <p>Start: Observed Seizure Event</p>
              </div>
              <div class="node-connector"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-level">
              <div class="decision-node">
                <div class="node-content">
                  <p>Is onset focal, generalized, or unknown?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="node-options">
                  <div class="option">Focal</div>
                  <div class="option">Generalized</div>
                  <div class="option">Unknown</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-level">
              <div class="decision-node focal">
                <div class="node-content">
                  <p>Is consciousness preserved or impaired?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="node-options">
                  <div class="option">Preserved</div>
                  <div class="option">Impaired</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="decision-node generalized">
                <div class="node-content">
                  <p>Is it motor or non-motor (absence)?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="node-options">
                  <div class="option">Motor</div>
                  <div class="option">Non-Motor</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="decision-node unknown">
                <div class="node-content">
                  <p>Is it motor, non-motor, or unclassified?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="node-options">
                  <div class="option">Motor</div>
                  <div class="option">Non-Motor</div>
                  <div class="option">Unclassified</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="decision-level">
              <div class="decision-node focal-preserved">
                <div class="node-content">
                  <p>Motor or non-motor onset?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="node-options">
                  <div class="option">Motor</div>
                  <div class="option">Non-Motor</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="decision-node focal-bilateral">
                <div class="node-content">
                  <p>Does it evolve to bilateral tonic-clonic?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="node-options">
                  <div class="option">Yes</div>
                  <div class="option">No</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Clinical Tips Section -->
        <div class="clinical-tips-section">
          <h3>Clinical Tips for Seizure Classification</h3>
          <div class="tips-container">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <div class="tip-number">1</div>
              <h4>History Taking</h4>
              <p>Ask for detailed description of the sequence of events, including any aura, motor manifestations, and recovery period. Query witnesses about the patient's responsiveness during the event.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <div class="tip-number">2</div>
              <h4>Video Documentation</h4>
              <p>When possible, have family members video record seizures on smartphones to aid classification.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <div class="tip-number">3</div>
              <h4>EEG Correlation</h4>
              <p>Correlate clinical features with EEG findings when available, especially for distinguishing focal from generalized onset.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <div class="tip-number">4</div>
              <h4>Consciousness Assessment</h4>
              <p>Test for preserved consciousness by asking the patient to recall specific details or perform simple tasks during the event.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <div class="tip-number">5</div>
              <h4>Reclassification</h4>
              <p>Be prepared to reclassify seizures as more information becomes available from additional witnesses, EEG studies, or imaging.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- EEG Findings by Seizure Type -->
        <div class="eeg-section">
          <h3>EEG Findings by Seizure Type</h3>
          <div class="eeg-table-container">
            <table class="eeg-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Seizure Type</th>
                  <th>Typical EEG Findings</th>
                  <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Focal with Preserved Consciousness</td>
                  <td>Rhythmic discharges in one region/hemisphere; may not always be visible on scalp EEG</td>
                  <td>Background slowing post-ictally may be focal</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Focal with Impaired Consciousness</td>
                  <td>Rhythmic theta/alpha/beta evolving to spike-waves in one hemisphere, often temporal</td>
                  <td>Background slowing post-ictally often lateralized</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Focal to Bilateral Tonic-Clonic</td>
                  <td>Focal onset with spread to both hemispheres; muscle artifact often obscures</td>
                  <td>Post-ictal slowing typically diffuse but may be lateralized</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Generalized Tonic-Clonic</td>
                  <td>Generalized spike-wave followed by electrodecremental pattern and fast activity</td>
                  <td>No focal onset recorded; post-ictal slowing is bilateral</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Absence</td>
                  <td>3 Hz (typical) or slower (atypical) generalized spike-wave discharges</td>
                  <td>Often induced by hyperventilation; minimal post-ictal changes</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Myoclonic</td>
                  <td>Generalized polyspike-wave discharges</td>
                  <td>Brief duration; often photosensitive</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Epileptic Spasms</td>
                  <td>Electrodecremental pattern or high-amplitude slow waves</td>
                  <td>May be focal, generalized, or have underlying hypsarrhythmia</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Unknown Onset</td>
                  <td>Variable, may have non-specific abnormalities</td>
                  <td>Further investigation often needed</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

